{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508444"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2754"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2754"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.03,0.02,0.69,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96782"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2754"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79397"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4457"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96782"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic four weeks after giving birth. She has a history of mild perinatal depression during pregnancy that was managed with psychological therapy. She reports worsening symptoms since delivery, including persistent low mood most days, difficulty coping with infant care, excessive guilt about her parenting abilities, insomnia, and poor appetite. While she can provide basic care for her baby, she lacks motivation for other activities. She denies thoughts of self-harm, suicidal ideation, or psychotic symptoms. She continues weekly psychology sessions but feels she needs additional support. She has no previous history of taking psychiatric medications. She is currently breastfeeding. Her postnatal recovery has been otherwise uncomplicated with normal blood test results.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antidepressant medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluoxetine","Duloxetine","Amitriptyline","Sertraline","Mirtazapine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with moderate-severe postnatal depression meeting DSM-5 criteria: depressed mood, excessive guilt, appetite changes, sleep disturbance, and anhedonia for more than two weeks postpartum. Her symptoms are significantly impacting function, having progressed from previously well-controlled mild depression during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it has minimal transfer into breast milk and extensive safety data in breastfeeding. It is the preferred SSRI for postnatal depression according to current guidelines, particularly when initiating new treatment in a breastfeeding mother.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E, while also an SSRI, has the highest concentration in breast milk of all SSRIs and should be avoided during breastfeeding due to potential risks to the infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuloxetine\u003C/strong\u003E, an SNRI, lacks adequate safety data in breastfeeding mothers and is not recommended as first-line therapy for postnatal depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmitriptyline\u003C/strong\u003E, a tricyclic antidepressant, has been associated with concerning side effects in breastfed infants including sedation and respiratory depression. While TCAs can be used safely in breastfeeding, they are generally reserved for women with previous good response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMirtazapine\u003C/strong\u003E, a NaSSA, has limited safety data in breastfeeding and is not recommended as first-line therapy. Although mirtazapine could potentially help with the patient\u0027s insomnia due to its sedating properties, an SSRI like sertraline would be more appropriate given the patient is currently breastfeeding and the extensive safety data available for sertraline in lactation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should involve collaboration with a perinatal mental health team where available. Continuing psychological therapy alongside medication is important, as is regular monitoring of maternal mental state and infant wellbeing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sertraline is the preferred SSRI for treating moderate-severe postnatal depression in breastfeeding mothers due to minimal transfer into breast milk.","Psychological therapy should be continued alongside medication for moderate-severe postnatal depression.","Risk assessment for self-harm and suicide is essential in postnatal depression."],"references":["Psychotropic use while breastfeeding. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd [Online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Field T. Breastfeeding and antidepressants. Infant Behav Dev. 2008;31(3):481-7. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2556848/","Mental Health Care in the Perinatal Period: Australian Clinical Practice Guideline. In: COPE: Centre of Perinatal Excellence. Perinatal depression [online]. 2017. Available at: https://cope.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Perinatal-Depression_Health-Prof.pdf."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data